<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0313 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0304EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-25 0479</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0501</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan vetoed a major trade bill forthe second time in three years, and the House swiftly countered byvoting to enact the measure over his objections.   In his veto message Tuesday, Reagan focused his objections on aprovision that would require companies to give their employeesnotice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.   Within hours, the House voted to override the veto, but it wasthought unlikely that the Senate would go along when it considersthe override after a Memorial Day recess.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders to the nation's factories for ``bigticket'' durable goods increased for the third consecutive month inApril, the government said.   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that orders for durablegoods, items expected to last three or more years, rose 0.8 percentlast month to a seasonally adjusted $116.3 billion. The climbfollowed gains of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1 percent in February.   Economists said the report was further evidence of animprovement in export demand.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Combined mid-May sales of domestically made carsand light trucks rose 2.6 percent from a year ago despite trimmingof buyer incentive lures, the auto companies reported.   Analysts on Tuesday blamed the lower car sales on leanerincentive offerings and on a rush in early May by buyers hurryingto beat the May 11 expiration of most major-maker incentives.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Home prices continued to skyrocket in severalNortheastern cities during the first three months of 1988, but thehot New York City market cooled somewhat after the October stockmarket crash, a real estate trade group said.   ``While trouble in the financial markets has affected certainpocket areas, like the area around New York City, the (Northeast)region as a whole is still exceptionally vigorous,'' John A.Tuccillo of the National Association of Realtors said Tuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committeescolded Reagan administration officials for offering ``pitiful''solutions for the stock market's problems, and promised to pressahead with his own bill.   Committee Chairman William Proxmire, D-Wis., used a hearingcalled by his panel Tuesday to lecture the authors of the WhiteHouse's latest crash report.   The high-ranking administration officials who produced thereport, released May 16, advanced several mild steps for soothingthe nation's volatile markets and nervous investors.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Steady ``downsizing'' of Eastern Airlines and thedraining of its assets and funds by parent Texas Air Corp. leavesthe Miami carrier with a precarious future, a union-commissionedstudy concludes.   The report released Tuesday was commissioned by the Air LinePilots Association.   In Washington, federally mediated hearings opened to settle abitter dispute between airline unions and Texas Air over whetherEastern and sister Continental Airlines should be considered asingle unit for bargaining purposes.</TEXT></DOC>